d147 5
a151 5
However, there is a large amount of third-party software one might want to
use in addition to the base system. The OpenBSD developers have done the
hard work to make many thousands of third-party applications available as
pre-compiled binary packages. These binary packages are then generally
managed with the pkg_* tools:
d154 7
a160 6
<li><a href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=pkg_add">pkg_add(1)</a>
to install or update a new package,
<li><a href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=pkg_delete">pkg_delete(1)</a>
to remove an installed package, and 
<li><a href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=pkg_info">pkg_info(1)</a>
to display package details such as a description of what the application does.
d176 3
a178 2
To get the most out of this handbook, you'll want to be very familiar with the
pkg_* tools and the base system. To learn more about packages, see
d182 1
a182 2
<b><font color="#e00000">
NOTE: The ports &amp; packages collection does NOT go through the
d186 1
a186 2
same level of robustness and security as in the base OS.
</font></b>
